claims:
1. A method for maintaining semantic content in a generated natural language text, the method comprising:
identifying at least one of words and phrases associated with the semantic content of a source text;
performing an evaluation of the source text, wherein the evaluation includes a summarization procedure, followed by a first measurement of a relative order and precedence of the at least one of the words and phrases in a source summarization result;
encoding the source text in a neural sequence-to-sequence encoder to generate a code;
sampling from a distribution implied by the code to create a candidate generated text;
performing an evaluation of the generated text, wherein the evaluation of the generated text includes a summarization procedure, followed by a second measurement of the relative order and precedence of the at least one of the words and phrases in a generated summarization result;
updating the internal weights associated with the encoder and decoder, based on a difference between the first measurement and second measurement.
2. The method of claim 1, wherein in response to the first difference being greater that a threshold, the encode, decode, and evaluation steps are repeated until the first difference is less than the threshold.
3. The method of claim 1, wherein the performing of the evaluation further comprises computing a source statistical measurement associated with a length and textual form of the source text, and wherein the evaluation of the generated text includes computing a generated statistical measurement comparable to the source statistical measurement and computing at least one statistical similarity measurement based on a comparison of the source statistical measurement and the generated statistical measurement.
4. The method of claim 1, wherein the performing of the evaluation further comprises computing a source readability measurement associated with a length and textual form of the source text, and wherein the evaluation of the generated text includes computing a generated readability measurement comparable to the source readability measurement and computing at least one readability similarity measurement based on a comparison of the source readability measurement and the generated readability measurement.
5. The method of claim 4, wherein the readability similarity measurement is compared relative to an expected reading capacity of a prospect.
